    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-05-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-05-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="132"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d132">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 774/83–90.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Rockhill</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>,<date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-05-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 17, 1907</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 619.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In continuation of my dispatch, No. 559, of March
                    15, in reference to the anti-opium movement in China, and particularly to the
                    measures being adopted by the Government to carry out the opium edict of
                    September 20, 1906.</p>
                <p>Within the last three weeks there has been issued by the Emperor a court order to
                    all officials impressing upon them the imperative necessity of exerting
                    themselves to the utmost to carry out the imperial commands, which we learn from
                    various sources have only been heeded in a few isolated sections of the country,
                    in this province and in the Two Kuang provinces particularly, where an active
                    anti-opium campaign is being conducted by the high provincial authorities.</p>
                <p>My personal opinion of the outcome of the present attempts at reform of the opium
                    traffic is that a Régie will ultimately be established, a measure which is
                    proving useful and profitable in Formosa, Java, and other countries.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. W. Rockhill.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
